[49m[38;5;9m- 368     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Late-arriving claims and the back-fill-behavior contract.** Many local encounters will not have a claim cluster at the time of initial linking because the claims have not arrived yet. Tag the encounter as awaiting_claims and re-evaluate on cluster arrival. The awaiting state has its own retention policy (an encounter with no claim cluster after 180 days is probably never going to get one, and gets re-tagged as billed_externally or non_billable). The pipeline operates on a sliding window (90 to 180 days default, with per-encounter-class tolerance). Each linkage record carries a `claims_completeness_estimate` (fraction of expected claims that have arrived based on the payer's historical arrival distribution) and a `next_review_date` (date by which remaining late-arriving claims would have arrived). Downstream consumers use these attributes to distinguish stable linkages from in-progress ones. Per-payer late-arrival metrics (median lag, p95 lag, completeness curves) are monitored with alarms on payer-specific degradation. Communicate the back-fill behavior to the analytics consumers explicitly, or you will spend a lot of time explaining why "the readmission rate for January looked different last week than it does this week."
